  <h2 class="text-center">Challenge</h2>
  <p>
    I was contacted by a former coworker looking for help with redesigning and improving the usability of the first version of their platform. The project began with evaluating the current site design to identify the issues impacting the user experience, overall user interface design and functionality. Based on my assessement make recommendations to the management team of the critical aspects of the designs that need to be made.
  </p>
  <p>
    Audience: Record labels, Entertainment companies, Companies that manage music festivals and tours, Small companies that want targeted advertising for their sales and marketing.
  </p>
  <h2 class="text-center"> Evaluation </h2>
  <p>
    My evaluation was focused on the following criteria. My recommendations also account for the mobile experience adaptation in the final design.
  </p>
  <ul class="criteria">
    <li>Navigation &amp; Information architecture</li>
    <li>Search</li>
    <li>Visual Design</li>
    <li>Page Layout &amp; Visualization</li>
  </ul>
  <h3> Navigation </h3>
  <div class="evaluation">
    <figure>
      <%= image_tag("muzit/trace-v1-navigation.png", alt: "Screenshot of Muzit version 1 navigation design", class: "responsive", height: "515", width: "1280") %>
    </figure>
  </div>
  <div class="summary full-bleed">
    <div class="container">
      <h4>Assessment</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>
          The Muzit admin related navigation is accessible from two areas of the navigation bar. One to manage accounts, campaigns, add a new artist and approve torrents. The other to update the user profile and log out. Not to say sidebars are bad but in this case impacts the visual hierarchy principle of proximity between the admin sidebar and the admin dropdown.
        </li>
        <li>
          Clicking the logo or &quot;TRACES&quot; directs the user to the same page which is redundant and not a standard navigation design convention.
        </li>
        <li>
          The icons and labels are misaligned.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
  <h3> Search </h3>
  <div class="evaluation">
    <figure>
      <%= image_tag("muzit/trace-v1-search.png", alt: "Screenshot of Muzit version 1 search results design", class: "responsive", height: "344", width: "1280") %>
    </figure>
  </div>
  <div class="summary full-bleed">
    <div class="container">
      <h4>Assessment</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>
          The icon is misaligned in relation to the search input field and background color makes it appear disabled.
        </li>
        <li>
          The search results dropdown width causes the &quot;Exisiting&quot; label to wrap if artist has a long name.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
  <h3> Visual Design </h3>
  <div class="evaluation">
    <h4 class="text-center">Dashboard</h4>
    <figure>
      <%= image_tag("muzit/trace-v1-dashboard.png", alt: "Screenshot of Muzit version 1 dashboard page design", class: "responsive", height: "681", width: "1250") %>
    </figure>
  </div>
  <div class="summary full-bleed">
    <div class="container">
      <h4>Assessment</h4>
      <ol>
        <li> The Artist Traces header and filter input do not expand to the full width of the viewport. </li>
        <li> The options button is misaligned and visually separated from the aritist image. The background color makes it appear disabled. The button is repeated for each artist on the dashboard which are in the hundreds adding visual clutter and contributing to cognitive overload. </li>
        <li> The artist options dropdown list items directs the user to the artist details page (see below). This requires the user to use the browser back button each time they need to perform a specifc action within the dropdown. </li>
        <li> When an artist image in not available the image appears broken. </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="evaluation">
    <h4 class="text-center"> Artist Details </h4>
    <figure>
      <%= image_tag("muzit/trace-v1-artist-details.png", alt: "Screenshot of Muzit version 1 artist details page design", class: "responsive", height: "1134", width: "1201") %>
    </figure>
  </div>
  <div class="summary full-bleed">
    <div class="container">
      <h4>Assessment</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Clicking &quot;Follow&quot; toggles the button state to &quot;Following&quot; as plain text. This is an affordance issue. The &quot;Following&quot; state should appear clickable to the user.
        </li>
        <li>
          The header statistics Total Downloaded Songs, Potential Reach and Torrents are misaligned in relation to the icons. The text size is inconsistent causing hierarchy and legibility issues.
        </li>
        <li>
          The date range filter dropdown is applied to each metric. Being able to change the date range for each individual metric would improve the user interaction.
        </li>
        <li>
          The Traffic Origins map visualization allows both macro views and granular views, down to a given state/province. Being able to click the Top Countries list text to drill down to a given state/province would improve the interactivity.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>
  <h2 class="text-center">Pivot</h2>
  <p>
    The management team decided the business model needed to pivot from delivering targeted email based advertising campaigns to providing targeted IP address lists to better leverage and monotize the data.
  </p>
  <p>
    I met with the CTO (who was also the chief architect and lead developer) to formulate an overall plan for the redesign and impact of the IP lists concept.
  </p>
  <h2 class="text-center">Plan</h2>
  <p>
    We established a timeline of deliverables broken into specifc phases.
  </p>
  <p>
    Some of the existing page types and concepts could still be used but an entirely new set of designs and functionality were needed for users to be able to generate, download and purchase the IP lists.
  </p>
  <p>
    Change the nomenclature to titles instead of artists as some of the torrents in the database are not artist related e.g. software, e-books, movies, etc.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li> which impacts the navigation and a </li>
  </ul>
  <h3>IP Lists Specification</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Lists would be collections of IP addresses based on titles, countries and regions.
    </li>
    <li>
      Users can add their own list.
    </li>
    <li>A List needs to be generated first because the number of IP addresses associated with a list changes by the second depending on download trends and real-time geographic data.</li>
    <li> When the list has been generated it is added to the Download Lists section and can be purchased using a credit card and an email will be sent with the purchase details. </li>
    <li>After a list is purchased a list it can be downloaded. </li>
  </ol>
